sentence: Crude climbs on Iranian nuclear energy comments .
Investing.com - Crude oil futures rose in Asian trading on Monday after Iran said it wo n't abandon its nuclear program , which the country insists is for peaceful , energy purposes .
Sentiment that Greece 's debt woes will drag on the European economy and crimp oil demand offset the commodity 's gains as did reports that Saudi Arabia has been hiking output .

On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light , sweet crude futures for delivery in July traded at USD92 .03 a barrel , up 0.25 % , off from a session high of USD92 .08 and up from an earlier session low of USD91 .14 .

News that Saudi Arabia was producing more crude than Russia in March pressured oil down early Monday , especially on the heels of reports that stockpiles have been rising in the U.S. Saudi Arabia hiked its daily output to 9.923 million barrels in March , the second-highest level since at least 1980 and more than Russia for the first time in six years , according to Bloomberg , citing Joint Organization Data Initiative data .
Saudi Arabia has been hiking output recently to counter any disruption stemming from pending conflict between Iran and the West .
The West has accused Iran of developing a nuclear weapons program , a charge Tehran denies , and sanctions slapped in the oil-rich Middle East country have already cut supplies bound to Europe .
Multilateral talks have opened to ease tensions , which have allowed oil prices to fall .
Iran has insisted its nuclear program serves the country 's energy needs , and leaders over the weekend vowed not to abandon the program .
`` We must pay close attention when we speak of oil revenues and sanctions against oil sales , who are the winners and the losers of such sanctions ? ''
Iranian Finance Minister Shamseddin Hosseini told CNN 's `` Fareed Zakaria GPS '' , adding prices could rise as high as USD160 a barrel if sanctions further cut Iranian crude .
`` There are conversations and dialogues taking place currently , but there can not be a hegemony and a double-standard in the treatment of member countries such as Iran , '' Hosseini said .
`` If these principles can be understood and applied with mutual respect , I think we will be in a much better place .
If we do n't , we will witness a increase in international oil markets . ''
On the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for July delivery were up 0.20 % and trading at USD107 .34 a barrel , up USD15 .31 from its U.S. counterpart .
